  "prompt": "Is money laundering subject to legal prosecution?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is subject to legal prosecution in virtually every country around the world. Money laundering is the illegal process of making large amounts of money generated by criminal activity, such as drug trafficking or terrorist funding, appear to have come from a legitimate source. It is a serious financial crime that undermines the integrity of financial systems and economies.\n\n### Legal Framework\n1. **International Standards**: Organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** set international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Countries that are part of FATF, including China, are required to implement measures to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities.\n\n2. **National Laws**: Most countries have specific laws criminalizing money laundering. For example:\n   - In **China**, the **Anti-Money Laundering Law** (enacted in 2007) and amendments to the **Criminal Law** define money laundering as a criminal offense.\n   - In the **United States**, the **Bank Secrecy Act** and the **Patriot Act** provide the legal framework for prosecuting money laundering.\n   - In the **European Union**, the **Anti-Money Laundering Directives** harmonize laws across member states.\n\n### Prosecution\nMoney laundering is prosecuted vigorously because it facilitates other criminal activities and poses significant risks to financial systems. Penalties for money laundering can include:\n- Heavy fines,\n- Confiscation of assets,\n- Imprisonment (often for several years),\n- Additional consequences for businesses, such as loss of licenses or severe reputational damage.\n\n### Enforcement\nEnforcement agencies, such as financial intelligence units (FIUs), law enforcement, and regulatory bodies, work together to investigate and prosecute money laundering cases. In China, the **People's Bank of China (PBOC)** and the **Ministry of Public Security** play key roles in enforcing anti-money laundering laws.\n\n### Conclusion\nMoney laundering is a serious criminal offense that is subject to legal prosecution globally. Governments and international organizations continuously work to strengthen laws and enforcement mechanisms to combat this illegal activity.",
